"name":"Haughton","meanings":["English: habitational name from Haughton (Cheshire, Lancashire, Northumberland, Shropshire, Staffordshire), or Haughton le Skerne (Durham). The placenames derive from Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Houghton  .","Irish: adopted for <b>Ó hEacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eachán</i>’, a pet form of the personal name <i>Eachaidh</i> (see   Hoey  ).","Irish: adopted for <b>Ó hEachtair</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eachtair</i>’, a personal name of uncertain origin. Compare   Hoctor  ."]},{"name":"Howton","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Houghton  ."]},{"name":"Hufton","meanings":["English: habitational name; probably from Stony Houghton in Pleasley (Derbyshire), the name of which derives from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Houghton  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Simon de Coughton was born about 1137, in Evesham, Worcestershire, England, his father, William de Coughton III, was 31 and his mother, Anne De Cocton, was 27. He married Mrs. Wrottesley de Cocton about 1178. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1199, in Wrottesley